It seems like it should do something to at least warn you though...

There are some cases where very wrong answers result.  For example, in 
multiphase problems, depending on how the polynomial fits are done for 
the condensed phases, condensed phases may be computed to be present at 
temperatures far above their melting or boiling point.  This results 
simply because the thermo fits for condensed phases are typically done 
only in the temperature range for which it is thermodynamically stable, 
and the polynomial may be non-monotonic outside this range. The 
multiphase solver handles this by only allowing condensed phases to 
exist at temperatures for which their thermo data are valid.

Of course if you really want to do a calculation outside the valid 
temperature range, you can always go in and edit the input cti file to 
change the temperature limits... Since cti files are really Python 
scripts, it is possible to set the temperature limits for species to 
symbolic values (e.g. TMIN or TMAX), and then near the top of the cti 
file add a line like:

TMAX = 6000.0

to change the max temperature for many species simultaneously.  Of 
course, this is much more cumbersome in the old NASA-format 4-line 
thermo data records.  Yet another reason to migrate away from the 
Chemkin/NASA file format and use cti format as the primary input 
format...

Dave




